00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:36.172
OK, but what is Bitcoin?

00:03:36.172 --> 00:03:36.880
How does it work?

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:39.652
What makes it worth
anything at all?

00:03:39.652 --> 00:03:41.110
Well in the simplest
terms, Bitcoin

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:43.300
is a form of commodity money.

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:46.240
When it was first
created in January 2009,

00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:50.080
its original promise was to
be a truly universal currency,

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:52.810
a form of electronic
cash that could be sent

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:54.430
around the globe in minutes.

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:56.530
That would work just
as well in New York

00:03:56.530 --> 00:03:59.080
as it did in New Delhi.

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:02.530
Transactions were anonymous, or
at least were supposed to be,

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.350
and it all happened on a network
that existed independently

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:07.561
of any government or bank.

00:04:07.561 --> 00:04:10.060
The interesting thing to me
when I first heard about Bitcoin

00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:14.140
was I knew that early internet
pioneers had always envisioned

00:04:14.140 --> 00:04:16.450
that a payment's
protocol would be woven

00:04:16.450 --> 00:04:18.610
into the fabric of the web.

00:04:18.610 --> 00:04:22.540
You've got a guy like Peter
Thiel who came a bit later.

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:24.970
When he was building PayPal,
his original ambition

00:04:24.970 --> 00:04:27.430
was to create an
internet currency that

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:31.090
would replace the US dollar
for online transactions.

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:33.400
What kept him from doing
that was not actually

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:35.230
the popping of the
dot com bubble,

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:39.430
it was 9/11 and the raft of
new financial regulations

00:04:39.430 --> 00:04:43.100
that came down in the wake
of the terrorist attacks.

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:44.962
They forced him to
pivot away from that.

00:04:44.962 --> 00:04:46.420
Because otherwise
PayPal would have

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:50.270
been accused of money laundering
and all sorts of other things.

00:04:50.270 --> 00:04:52.750
So the brilliant thing that
Satoshi Nakamoto, the creator

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.255
of Bitcoin, did is he
didn't found a new company

00:04:55.255 --> 00:04:56.590
like PayPal.

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:59.080
Instead, he built a
decentralized system

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:02.650
that no one would own, but
anyone could participate in.

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:05.350
You'd have this
constantly updated copy

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:07.990
of the ledger recording
all the transactions that

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:10.300
would be stored on
the computer of anyone

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:13.720
on the network, anyone
running the open source

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:16.390
software of Bitcoin.

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:18.670
So it started out as the
money of the internet.

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:21.130
But gradually as
people began to think

00:05:21.130 --> 00:05:24.490
about its underlying technology
and take a closer look at it,

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:28.935
they began to refer to it
as the internet of money.

00:05:28.935 --> 00:05:30.310
The technology
underlying Bitcoin

00:05:30.310 --> 00:05:32.050
is called the blockchain.

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:33.550
It's basically a
tamper proof ledger

00:05:33.550 --> 00:05:35.590
for recording and
verifying transactions,

00:05:35.590 --> 00:05:41.170
which admittedly sounds like the
least sexy thing in the world.

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:42.820
But the revolutionary
thing about it

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:44.700
is that it allows
for transactions

00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:47.220
to be recorded and
verified without the need

00:05:47.220 --> 00:05:48.937
for a central authority.

00:05:48.937 --> 00:05:51.270
So normally that would be a
payments company like PayPal

00:05:51.270 --> 00:05:53.625
or it would be a bank or
it would be a government

00:05:53.625 --> 00:05:56.070
or it would be some
combination of the two

00:05:56.070 --> 00:05:58.710
like the Federal Reserve.

00:05:58.710 --> 00:06:00.960
But businesses and services
of blockchain technology

00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:04.120
can be decentralized, which
simultaneously cuts out

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:06.630
middlemen that add
cost to the system,

00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:08.670
and it removes any
single points of failure

00:06:08.670 --> 00:06:11.190
in the system at the same time.

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:13.652
This is disruptive to
a lot of businesses.

00:06:13.652 --> 00:06:16.110
One of the interesting things
when I was working on my book

00:06:16.110 --> 00:06:19.740
was to dig into the
international financial system

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:23.209
and find out just where
Bitcoin could be most useful.

00:06:23.209 --> 00:06:24.750
One of the biggest
areas I discovered

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:26.790
was cross-border payments.

00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:29.460
So basically the
way it works today,

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:32.190
when banks want to send
money across borders,

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:35.220
they use what's called the
corresponding banking system.

00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:38.550
A payment might have to make
as many as five different hops

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:41.312
to get to where it's
ultimately going across all

00:06:41.312 --> 00:06:43.020
of these different
financial institutions

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:45.850
and be exchanged from
one currency to another.

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:48.330
Typically when a bank
wants to send money

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:50.400
to another bank across
borders, it first

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:56.080
has to be holding cash at
that other institution.

00:06:56.080 --> 00:06:57.540
This cash is just
kind of dormant.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:07:00.420
It's dead cash that just
sits there waiting until they

00:07:00.420 --> 00:07:03.030
need to make payments with it.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:04.440
This is hugely wasteful.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:06.540
That cash isn't doing
anything for them

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:08.590
until they have to
make the payments.

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:11.220
Then on the consumer level,
you have remittances.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:14.970
This is when immigrants want to
send money back to their loved

00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:17.430
ones in their home countries.

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:20.520
They usually use Western
Union or MoneyGram today,

00:07:20.520 --> 00:07:22.620
and they get charged
really high fees.

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:26.310
So migrants from Sub-Saharan
Africa, for instance,

00:07:26.310 --> 00:07:30.300
pay an average of 9.81%
when they send money home.

00:07:30.300 --> 00:07:34.230
The global average is 7.45%,
which itself is really high.

00:07:34.230 --> 00:07:37.680
But you might notice there
that often the poorest

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:39.510
and the people that
are suffering the most

00:07:39.510 --> 00:07:42.750
have to end up paying
the highest fees.

00:07:42.750 --> 00:07:46.470
Well, remittances are a
$600 billion market today.

00:07:46.470 --> 00:07:49.290
The idea is that Bitcoin or
maybe another digital currency

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:53.280
that surpasses it has a chance
to grab a piece of that market

00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:54.840
while putting
billions of dollars

00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:57.870
back into people's pockets.

00:07:57.870 --> 00:08:00.450
Today in fact there's a
venture backed company called

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:02.420
Abra, which is doing just that.

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:05.310
It's using Bitcoin to
provide cheaper remittances

00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:08.727
to more than 100 countries.

00:08:08.727 --> 00:08:10.560
But what people realized
was that the things

00:08:10.560 --> 00:08:12.270
you store and transmit
on a blockchain

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:14.200
doesn't have to be money.

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:16.230
So one of the first
guys to realize this

00:08:16.230 --> 00:08:18.840
was the venture capitalist,
Marc Andreessen.

00:08:18.840 --> 00:08:20.610
He wrote an op ed for
"The New York Times"

00:08:20.610 --> 00:08:24.570
way back in January 2014
in which he called Bitcoin

00:08:24.570 --> 00:08:26.940
not a digital currency,
not a form of money.

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:29.640
He called it a digital
bearer instrument,

00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:32.789
a way of exchanging assets
and confirming their ownership

00:08:32.789 --> 00:08:34.409
over the internet.

00:08:34.409 --> 00:08:37.110
Those assets could be
digital currency, of course.

00:08:37.110 --> 00:08:41.490
They could be the titles and
deeds to physical property.

00:08:41.490 --> 00:08:43.590
They could be stocks and bonds.

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:47.107
They could be a number
of different assets.

00:08:47.107 --> 00:08:49.440
So this is the reason the
world's biggest banks and tech

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:51.360
companies are all setting
up blockchain labs

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:54.270
and working groups and
building proofs of concept.

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:58.080
This is the reason Bitcoin and
blockchain startups have raised

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:00.630
something like $1.6
billion of investment

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:03.300
capital in the past few years.

00:09:03.300 --> 00:09:06.060
Their investors
include names you

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:10.980
might know, like GV,
Goldman Sachs, Visa,

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:15.750
Capital One, NASDAQ, and
The New York Stock Exchange.

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:19.080
Now if that isn't enough,
the interesting thing

00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:21.300
also is that Bitcoin has
actually inspired people

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:24.090
to create other crypto
currencies, some of which

00:09:24.090 --> 00:09:27.900
have features that arguably
make them superior to Bitcoin.

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.680
Then even more than that,
many of the hottest blockchain

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:33.490
assets today are not
digital currencies at all.

00:09:33.490 --> 00:09:35.430
They're these things
called tokens.

00:09:35.430 --> 00:09:37.511
They don't have blockchain
networks of their own

00:09:37.511 --> 00:09:38.010
to run on.

00:09:38.010 --> 00:09:41.160
Instead, they run on top of an
existing blockchain network,

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:43.380
such as Bitcoins or Ethereums.

00:09:43.380 --> 00:09:45.820
They tend to be purpose built
for specific applications.

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:48.750
So there's one
called Golem which

00:09:48.750 --> 00:09:52.074
is meant to power a peer to peer
marketplace for computation.

00:09:52.074 --> 00:09:53.490
There's one called
Augur, which is

00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:57.810
for a crowdsourced
prediction market and so on.

00:09:57.810 --> 00:09:59.644
Dozens of these tokens
have launched so far.

00:09:59.644 --> 00:10:01.518
Some of you have probably
seen the headlines.

00:10:01.518 --> 00:10:03.480
They've been raising
huge amounts of capital

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:06.180
in unbelievably short
amounts of time.

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:08.630
One raised $10
million in six hours.

00:10:08.630 --> 00:10:12.960
Then another raised $35
million in 30 seconds.

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:16.740
Another raised $150
million in an hour or two.

00:10:19.290 --> 00:10:23.490
The amount raised now for
these software projects

00:10:23.490 --> 00:10:27.510
through this new token
model has actually

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:29.160
surpassed the amount
of money that's

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:30.660
been put in by
traditional venture

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:34.290
capitalists into this
industry so far this year.

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:36.320
That itself is
over $200 million,

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:39.346
so it's nothing to sneeze at.

00:10:39.346 --> 00:10:41.220
So dozens of these tokens
have been launched,

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:43.520
and dozens more
are on the horizon.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:44.990
People are starting
to think this

00:10:44.990 --> 00:10:49.350
might yield the second
business model of the internet.

00:10:49.350 --> 00:10:51.920
To see why, I think
it helps to think

00:10:51.920 --> 00:10:53.990
about what the current
business model is, right?

00:10:53.990 --> 00:10:56.300
So take Facebook.

00:10:56.300 --> 00:11:00.040
If Facebook had issued
a token to its users,

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:01.640
its value, we could
imagine, would

00:11:01.640 --> 00:11:04.070
derive from the
content and connections

00:11:04.070 --> 00:11:06.410
that are generated on Facebook.

00:11:06.410 --> 00:11:08.862
Now, early users, when it was
just restricted to college

00:11:08.862 --> 00:11:10.820
students-- there weren't
many people on there--

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:12.695
they might have been
able to kind of scoop up

00:11:12.695 --> 00:11:16.220
a large number of these
tokens at cheap prices.

00:11:16.220 --> 00:11:18.890
Then later users who kind of
jumped on the bandwagon later

00:11:18.890 --> 00:11:22.010
as the value of the
platform became apparent,

00:11:22.010 --> 00:11:24.170
maybe they'd only be
able to afford a few.

00:11:24.170 --> 00:11:27.050
But all of them, by holding
this liquid digital asset,

00:11:27.050 --> 00:11:32.300
would be able to participate
in Facebook's growing success.

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:34.910
That, of course, is not how
Facebook operates, right?

00:11:34.910 --> 00:11:38.360
We know that the $450
billion value of Facebook

00:11:38.360 --> 00:11:40.520
accrues mainly to
Mark Zuckerberg

00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:42.980
and the other shareholders.

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:44.630
Most other internet
platforms operate

00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:49.550
in a similar way, Twitter,
Tumblr, Instagram, even Etsy.

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:52.190
The owners of these
platforms are not actually

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:55.850
producing content themselves,
but they extract massive value

00:11:55.850 --> 00:11:58.910
from the interactions
between users.

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:01.250
This has become so
common and so accepted

00:12:01.250 --> 00:12:03.440
that it's actually
difficult to imagine

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:05.540
a different kind of setup.

00:12:05.540 --> 00:12:07.910
With decentralized systems
based on blockchain tokens,

00:12:07.910 --> 00:12:10.610
though, there's no longer
a division or no longer

00:12:10.610 --> 00:12:13.790
such a clear division at least
between the users and owners.

00:12:13.790 --> 00:12:16.430
The tokens become a
wealth sharing mechanism,

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:19.260
which is a way that everyone,
even the average consumers,

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:21.560
the average users,
can get a piece

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:23.610
of the future of the internet.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:25.610
So the token is kind
of a unit of account

00:12:25.610 --> 00:12:29.600
that prices users back in.

00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:31.100
It doesn't even end there.

00:12:31.100 --> 00:12:32.600
In a couple of years
I'm told we can

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:36.320
expect to see something
called [? perichains. ?]

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:38.270
Think of it as a kind
of connective glue

00:12:38.270 --> 00:12:40.520
that would allow all the
different blockchain networks

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:42.230
to communicate with each other.

00:12:42.230 --> 00:12:45.650
So right now they're isolated,
but with [? perichains, ?]

00:12:45.650 --> 00:12:48.502
applications and smart
contracts built on one system

00:12:48.502 --> 00:12:50.210
would be able to
interact with the assets

00:12:50.210 --> 00:12:53.270
and data on the other systems.

00:12:53.270 --> 00:12:56.390
So users could flow easily from
one to the next to the next,

00:12:56.390 --> 00:12:58.910
strengthening the
whole ecosystem.

00:12:58.910 --> 00:13:01.370
As long as you're keyed
into any cryptocurrency,

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:05.060
you'd have access to
every cryptocurrency.

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:06.980
Because of this, the
CEO of a hedge fund

00:13:06.980 --> 00:13:10.820
recently told me that he expects
in 10 years the total market

00:13:10.820 --> 00:13:13.640
cap of all blockchain assets
will be at least $1 trillion.

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:20.410
The last thing I want to say
is that the effects of Bitcoin

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:22.620
and blockchain technology
won't be felt only

00:13:22.620 --> 00:13:26.622
on the internet or only
in the realm of finance.

00:13:26.622 --> 00:13:28.080
I think Bitcoin
actually represents

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:31.350
a counterforce to some of
the most troubling trends

00:13:31.350 --> 00:13:35.710
of our time, which is the
rising tide of nationalism,

00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:40.950
populism, trade protectionism,
and all of this stuff

00:13:40.950 --> 00:13:46.840
that we're seeing in the US,
the UK, and across Europe.

00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:49.020
So until 2016, I
think for many of us

00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:53.520
the world appeared to be moving
inexorably toward open borders,

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:57.840
economic inclusion, closer
alliances between nations,

00:13:57.840 --> 00:13:59.340
right?

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:02.610
The narrative was that our
global citizenry was rejecting

00:14:02.610 --> 00:14:05.700
the old prejudice of
nationalism and tribalism,

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:10.650
and history was describing a
more and more wonderful arc.

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:12.384
Well, then we had Brexit, right?

00:14:12.384 --> 00:14:14.050
Then we had the
election of Donald Trump

00:14:14.050 --> 00:14:16.080
and we have the refugee crisis.

00:14:16.080 --> 00:14:19.180
That kind of changed
our way of thinking.

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:22.590
But there is still another story
happening at the same time.

00:14:22.590 --> 00:14:25.640
I think it's one that many
of us are participating in.

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:28.020
It's about how the way
that people live and work

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:29.130
is changing.

00:14:29.130 --> 00:14:31.110
It's about the fact that
international travel

00:14:31.110 --> 00:14:33.840
is easier than ever, the fact
that technologies like Skype

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:37.470
have expanded our reach, the
fact that a lot of young people

00:14:37.470 --> 00:14:40.470
today see themselves more
as citizens of the world

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:43.020
or of some internet
subculture than they

00:14:43.020 --> 00:14:47.280
do their countries of origin.

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:50.790
So the time really is ripe for
a universal digital currency

00:14:50.790 --> 00:14:53.640
and for the other technologies
that it makes possible.

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:57.360
Bitcoin is that currency, or
is at least the first version

00:14:57.360 --> 00:14:59.550
of that currency.

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:02.460
I noticed while writing my
book, and it's still true today,

00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:06.270
that very few Bitcoin or
blockchain startups are focused

00:15:06.270 --> 00:15:09.592
only on developing nations.

00:15:09.592 --> 00:15:10.800
That's to be expected, right?

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:14.160
Because cryptocurrency is a
tool of international inclusion.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:15.630
Its advocates tend
to be committed

00:15:15.630 --> 00:15:19.080
to open borders and
the free flow of people

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:22.206
and ideas and capital.

00:15:22.206 --> 00:15:25.440
Naval Ravikant, the CEO of
AngelList, one of the smartest

00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:28.980
guys in Silicon Valley,
