was written into the software

00:18:12.270 --> 00:18:15.630
that the more processing
power that's applied,

00:18:15.630 --> 00:18:17.340
the more difficult
they will become.

00:18:17.340 --> 00:18:19.290
So they would become more
difficult over time anyway.

00:18:19.290 --> 00:18:20.873
And then also the
more people that get

00:18:20.873 --> 00:18:23.880
involved and try to do this,
the more difficult it becomes.

00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:25.860
So at first, when there
were only a few people,

00:18:25.860 --> 00:18:27.385
you could do it with your GPU--

00:18:27.385 --> 00:18:28.555
or with your CPU, sorry.

00:18:28.555 --> 00:18:30.180
Then it became a
little more difficult.

00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:31.860
People started
using their GPUs--

00:18:31.860 --> 00:18:34.720
their graphics
processors-- to do this.

00:18:34.720 --> 00:18:37.020
Then even that
became insufficient.

00:18:37.020 --> 00:18:38.580
And people started
building ASICs,

00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:40.110
which are these
application-specific

00:18:40.110 --> 00:18:44.620
processors, just
to mine bitcoins.

00:18:44.620 --> 00:18:47.400
And then that turned
into an arms race.

00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:50.010
And now you have what are
called mining pools, which

00:18:50.010 --> 00:18:53.160
are basically people
with incredibly powerful,

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:55.802
sophisticated machines--

00:18:55.802 --> 00:18:57.510
not even terribly
sophisticated, frankly,

00:18:57.510 --> 00:18:59.670
but just very powerful.

00:18:59.670 --> 00:19:03.060
And they're all pooling their
computer resources together.

00:19:03.060 --> 00:19:05.460
And then they kind of
share in the rewards

00:19:05.460 --> 00:19:08.670
because it's a race to
confirm the transactions

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:10.560
and then get the bitcoins
every 10 minutes.

