00:33:07.594 --> 00:33:09.260
A traditional economist
would look at it

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:11.480
and say, how can these
be currencies when

00:33:11.480 --> 00:33:13.260
their value fluctuates so much?

00:33:13.260 --> 00:33:15.320
They can't be used as a
stable unit of account,

00:33:15.320 --> 00:33:17.600
that basically the
three qualities that

00:33:17.600 --> 00:33:19.550
make something a
currency typically

00:33:19.550 --> 00:33:22.907
are that it's a store of value,
which bitcoin certainly is.

00:33:22.907 --> 00:33:24.740
You're talking about
people trying to use it

00:33:24.740 --> 00:33:26.330
as a store of value, right.

00:33:26.330 --> 00:33:28.190
It's a unit of exchange,
which bitcoin is.

00:33:28.190 --> 00:33:32.327
It can be used to buy goods and
services or sent peer to peer.

00:33:32.327 --> 00:33:34.410
But then the third is that
it's a unit of account.

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:37.910
And that is one that bitcoin's
not really used for that today.

00:33:37.910 --> 00:33:41.559
And it's partly because
the price is so volatile.

00:33:41.559 --> 00:33:43.100
But there's another
school of thought

00:33:43.100 --> 00:33:46.400
that says, actually,
the volatility is OK.

00:33:46.400 --> 00:33:49.670
The speculation is OK
because before bitcoin

00:33:49.670 --> 00:33:53.480
can become a truly global
currency that can really

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:56.340
serve a huge global user base--

00:33:56.340 --> 00:33:57.770
and actually it's
worth mentioning

00:33:57.770 --> 00:34:01.190
that a month or two ago, a study
out of Cambridge University

00:34:01.190 --> 00:34:04.250
found that the number of people
now using cryptocurrencies

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:07.714
worldwide rivals the
population of small countries.

00:34:07.714 --> 00:34:08.880
So that's pretty impressive.

00:34:08.880 --> 00:34:13.489
But even that, it's not a
giant global user base, right?

00:34:13.489 --> 00:34:15.260
But they say right
now the market cap

00:34:15.260 --> 00:34:19.219
of bitcoin's in the $30
billions or about $40 billion

00:34:19.219 --> 00:34:21.679
or something like that.

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:24.320
Really, its market cap needs
to be much higher, I think,

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:26.530
before it can serve a
truly global user base.

00:34:26.530 --> 00:34:30.199
It needs to be maybe
even 10 times higher

00:34:30.199 --> 00:34:33.409
when you compare it to
the amount of US dollars

00:34:33.409 --> 00:34:35.449
that are out there,
for instance.

00:34:35.449 --> 00:34:37.250
So actually, the
speculation is OK.

00:34:37.250 --> 00:34:38.958
The fact that some
people are hoarding it

00:34:38.958 --> 00:34:42.590
might be OK because if it
makes it more valuable,

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:46.820
if it makes it more scarce,
and that drives the price up,

00:34:46.820 --> 00:34:51.199
that might be when we see its
function as a currency start

00:34:51.199 --> 00:34:53.635
to really come to the fore.

00:34:53.635 --> 00:34:55.010
The other answer
to your question

00:34:55.010 --> 00:34:58.190
is that there are actually
technological solutions

00:34:58.190 --> 00:35:01.080
to the volatility that allow it
to still be used as a currency.

00:35:01.080 --> 00:35:04.700
So for instance,
payment processors who

00:35:04.700 --> 00:35:06.980
exists in the bitcoin
industry today,

00:35:06.980 --> 00:35:10.190
they are willing to take
on that volatility risk

00:35:10.190 --> 00:35:11.310
on behalf of the merchant.

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:14.900
So if you have bitcoins, and
you want to use them to buy

00:35:14.900 --> 00:35:19.730
bedsheets or something like
that from Overstock.com--

00:35:19.730 --> 00:35:21.560
and they do accept bitcoins--

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:23.480
you will send the
bitcoins to Overstock.

00:35:23.480 --> 00:35:26.220
But Overstock actually won't be
exposed to the volatility risk.

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:28.280
They don't handle the
bitcoins themselves.

00:35:28.280 --> 00:35:31.520
It gets accepted for them
by their merchant, payment

00:35:31.520 --> 00:35:34.070
provider, which I believe
for them is Coinbase,

00:35:34.070 --> 00:35:35.900
or it might be a
company called BitPay.

00:35:35.900 --> 00:35:38.720
That company then will
exchange the currency for them

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:41.262
almost immediately
and give them the cash

00:35:41.262 --> 00:35:43.220
that they want to keep
as their unit of account

00:35:43.220 --> 00:35:44.630
for their bookkeeping.

00:35:44.630 --> 00:35:48.620
And you're happy because you got
to spend your digital currency

00:35:48.620 --> 00:35:49.821
the way you wanted to.

00:35:49.821 --> 00:35:52.070
The merchant is happy because
they got the US dollars.

00:35:52.070 --> 00:35:54.350
And the merchant
services provider

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:56.900
is happy because they
made a little percentage

00:35:56.900 --> 00:35:58.110
on that transaction.

00:35:58.110 --> 00:35:59.860
So you know--

00:35:59.860 --> 00:36:02.119
AUDIENCE: OK, thank you.

00:36:02.119 --> 00:36:02.702
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:36:02.702 --> 00:36:03.658
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:36:03.658 --> 00:36:06.660
I was curious to see what your
thoughts on the flippening are

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:09.810
and where you see, like, the
bitcoin-versus-ethereum debate

00:36:09.810 --> 00:36:12.450
going and what maybe the
advantages and disadvantages

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:14.610
of the two are.

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:18.042
BRIAN PATRICK EHA: Yeah, I
mean, so really big question.

00:36:18.042 --> 00:36:19.500
What he's talking
about is the idea

00:36:19.500 --> 00:36:21.560
that some people
have that ethereum

00:36:21.560 --> 00:36:24.030
is going to overtake bitcoin
in terms of its market cap,

00:36:24.030 --> 00:36:27.084
in terms of its just
overall use case,

00:36:27.084 --> 00:36:29.250
that maybe there aren't
that many things bitcoin can

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:30.870
do that ethereum can't do.

00:36:30.870 --> 00:36:32.400
Ethereum right
now is the world's

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:36.870
second-biggest cryptocurrency by
market cap, by number of users,

00:36:36.870 --> 00:36:39.430
and so on.

00:36:39.430 --> 00:36:44.429
As a journalist, I kind
of cherish the fact

00:36:44.429 --> 00:36:45.970
that I can be somewhat
of an observer

00:36:45.970 --> 00:36:48.760
and not have to, like,
take a very partisan side

00:36:48.760 --> 00:36:50.927
because there are
a lot of partisans

00:36:50.927 --> 00:36:52.510
right now in the
cryptocurrency space.

00:36:52.510 --> 00:36:55.420
And you can talk to one guy,
and he'll swear up and down

00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:57.719
that ethereum is
practically a scam

00:36:57.719 --> 00:36:59.260
and that there's no
reason you should

00:36:59.260 --> 00:37:00.280
use anything but bitcoin.

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:01.738
And then there are
other people who

00:37:01.738 --> 00:37:04.050
say ethereum's more
sophisticated than bitcoin.

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:09.260
And I think they somewhat
have different use cases.

00:37:09.260 --> 00:37:12.520
And I do think that bitcoin
today still has an incredibly

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:15.740
strong first mover advantage.

00:37:15.740 --> 00:37:19.180
It has an unparalleled network
effect, unparalleled name

00:37:19.180 --> 00:37:20.230
recognition.

00:37:20.230 --> 00:37:22.392
If I go to the average
person and I say,

00:37:22.392 --> 00:37:24.100
have you heard of
bitcoin, they might not

00:37:24.100 --> 00:37:25.058
know anything about it.

00:37:25.058 --> 00:37:27.130
But they might say, yeah,
that sounds familiar.

00:37:27.130 --> 00:37:28.240
But if I say, do you
know what ethereum

00:37:28.240 --> 00:37:29.700
is, they're going
to probably say,

00:37:29.700 --> 00:37:32.170
I have no idea what
you're talking about.

00:37:32.170 --> 00:37:34.690
And frankly, that is one of
the first obstacles ethereum

00:37:34.690 --> 00:37:37.890
would have to overcome.

00:37:37.890 --> 00:37:39.940
I think we know from
the technology space

00:37:39.940 --> 00:37:42.460
that in order for one
service or one product

00:37:42.460 --> 00:37:45.730
to overtake a rival one, it
can't just be like 10% better,

00:37:45.730 --> 00:37:46.360
right?

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:50.170
It needs to be twice as good or
five times as good sometimes.

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:52.660
And I'm not sure for
most people ethereum

00:37:52.660 --> 00:37:54.300
fits those
qualifications right now,

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:56.830
especially, I mean,
bitcoin right now

00:37:56.830 --> 00:37:59.680
is having some trouble
scaling the network up

00:37:59.680 --> 00:38:02.380
to serve a global user base.

00:38:02.380 --> 00:38:04.450
Transactions are taking longer.

00:38:04.450 --> 00:38:07.140
They're becoming more
costly and so on.

00:38:07.140 --> 00:38:09.670
I mean, the transactions
themselves are instantaneous.

00:38:09.670 --> 00:38:12.730
But the time it takes to confirm
the transactions on the network

00:38:12.730 --> 00:38:15.820
to verify that they're
valid, that's taking longer.

00:38:15.820 --> 00:38:17.320
So some people were
saying, oh yeah,

00:38:17.320 --> 00:38:20.770
bitcoin is like becoming
a stick in the mud.

00:38:20.770 --> 00:38:22.660
All those people-- the
competing stakeholders

00:38:22.660 --> 00:38:24.941
in the bitcoin system--
they can't work out

00:38:24.941 --> 00:38:25.690
their differences.

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:27.439
They can't come to
agreement on a proposal

00:38:27.439 --> 00:38:29.760
for how to upgrade the
software and move forward

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:31.900
to scale the network.

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:34.360
So obviously, ethereum is
just going to eat its lunch.

00:38:34.360 --> 00:38:38.080
But we just this past week saw
some problems with the ethereum

00:38:38.080 --> 00:38:40.180
network, where transactions
were getting clogged,

00:38:40.180 --> 00:38:41.656
and there were some issues.

00:38:41.656 --> 00:38:43.030
So I think that
took the wind out

00:38:43.030 --> 00:38:46.450
of the sails of a lot of people
that previously had thought,

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:50.390
like, it's just clear sailing
for ethereum from here on out.

00:38:50.390 --> 00:38:50.945
So--

00:38:50.945 --> 00:38:51.778
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:51.778 --> 00:38:52.837
BRIAN PATRICK EHA: Yeah.

00:38:52.837 --> 00:38:54.420
AUDIENCE: Hey, great
to have you here.

00:38:54.420 --> 00:38:55.450
BRIAN PATRICK EHA: Sure.

00:38:55.450 --> 00:38:58.270
AUDIENCE: Such an astonishing
five years in the crypto world.

00:38:58.270 --> 00:39:01.120
And it's all very exciting,
with distributed applications

00:39:01.120 --> 00:39:01.670
and so on.

00:39:01.670 --> 00:39:03.910
But as you know, Mike
Hearn is probably

00:39:03.910 --> 00:39:06.450
the most famous Googler
that advocated for bitcoin

00:39:06.450 --> 00:39:08.320
and joined the
bitcoin corp. And he

00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:11.470
quit because of infighting
and debates over the direction

00:39:11.470 --> 00:39:12.880
that it should take.

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:14.434
Given the amount
of trust that has

00:39:14.434 --> 00:39:19.480
to be placed in the developers
for these different coins

00:39:19.480 --> 00:39:21.370
and the amount of
infighting that goes on--

00:39:21.370 --> 00:39:22.370
BRIAN PATRICK EHA: Yeah.

00:39:24.730 --> 00:39:27.760
AUDIENCE: --are we still blocked
on some kind of governance

00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:33.640
solution to actually make these
kinds of things successful?

00:39:36.299 --> 00:39:37.840
BRIAN PATRICK EHA:
Well, that's where

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:39.730
some of the
alternatives to bitcoin

00:39:39.730 --> 00:39:43.090
become potentially interesting.

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:45.940
There's one called Dash,
which some people think

00:39:45.940 --> 00:39:49.660
in terms of its innovations
as a form of digital cash

00:39:49.660 --> 00:39:51.460
or cryptocurrency or
whatever it might not

00:39:51.460 --> 00:39:53.944
be a huge improvement
over bitcoin.

00:39:53.944 --> 00:39:55.360
What's really
interesting about it

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:59.170
is its innovation in
the governance model.

00:39:59.170 --> 00:40:04.810
So with Dash, basically, the
network kind of administrators,

00:40:04.810 --> 00:40:06.790
in a sense, are people
running these things

00:40:06.790 --> 00:40:08.284
called master nodes.

00:40:08.284 --> 00:40:09.700
And in order to
run a master node,

00:40:09.700 --> 00:40:11.860
you have to own at
least 1,000 Dash.

00:40:11.860 --> 00:40:15.400
So you have to be very much
a stakeholder in the network.

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:20.380
And then proposals
for doing marketing

00:40:20.380 --> 00:40:23.620
for the network, proposals
to upgrade the software,

00:40:23.620 --> 00:40:26.650
add new features, or
any number of things--

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:30.640
they all on a monthly
basis get put up for a vote

00:40:30.640 --> 00:40:33.850
by all of the people
running master nodes.

00:40:33.850 --> 00:40:35.559
Now it's still a
decentralized system.

00:40:35.559 --> 00:40:37.600
In fact, many of the people
running master nodes,

00:40:37.600 --> 00:40:40.090
it's not even known
who they are exactly.

00:40:40.090 --> 00:40:42.220
And one individual could
run, theoretically,

00:40:42.220 --> 00:40:43.325
more than one master node.

00:40:43.325 --> 00:40:44.950
But there are thousands
of master nodes

00:40:44.950 --> 00:40:46.510
right now on the network.

00:40:46.510 --> 00:40:49.750
And even the development team
for Dash is actually beholden

00:40:49.750 --> 00:40:53.620
to their approval because the
way Dash works is that some

00:40:53.620 --> 00:40:56.920
of the new Dash coins-- if
you want to call them that--

00:40:56.920 --> 00:41:00.070
that are created every
month, they actually

00:41:00.070 --> 00:41:03.400
get allocated as funding
for the developers

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:05.500
to pay the developer
talent and so

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:08.620
on to keep working on
the system, improving it,

00:41:08.620 --> 00:41:09.700
and so on.

00:41:09.700 --> 00:41:12.100
But they have to
actually propose

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:13.810
to the stakeholders
of the network,

00:41:13.810 --> 00:41:15.770
this is what we'd like to do.

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:18.370
And then there's a
democratic process

00:41:18.370 --> 00:41:20.050
in which that gets voted on.

00:41:20.050 --> 00:41:23.290
And sometimes their
proposals don't pass.

00:41:23.290 --> 00:41:26.175
But it's a way to kind of keep
the developers honest and keep

00:41:26.175 --> 00:41:28.550
the interests, I think, of
all the different stakeholders

00:41:28.550 --> 00:41:29.860
in the network aligned.

00:41:29.860 --> 00:41:32.320
The developers rely on
them for their funding.

00:41:32.320 --> 00:41:33.790
At the same time,
the stakeholders

00:41:33.790 --> 00:41:37.300
rely on the developers in
order to keep the network going

00:41:37.300 --> 00:41:41.070
strong, which makes their Dash
coins valuable and incentivizes

00:41:41.070 --> 00:41:43.890
them to run the master nodes
in the first place and so on.

00:41:43.890 --> 00:41:48.060
So that, to me, is a really
interesting governance model.

00:41:48.060 --> 00:41:50.482
I don't know whether Dash
will one day replace bitcoin

00:41:50.482 --> 00:41:51.690
for that reason or something.

00:41:51.690 --> 00:41:54.570
But people are starting to
innovate, not just on aspects

00:41:54.570 --> 00:41:58.080
of the technology itself
but on aspects of the way

00:41:58.080 --> 00:42:00.690
that these decentralized
networks are governed.

00:42:00.690 --> 00:42:04.650
And yeah, I mean, bitcoin
is very much the 1.0.

00:42:04.650 --> 00:42:07.350
It's had to go through
all these growing pains.

00:42:07.350 --> 00:42:10.110
And people didn't know
how this stuff would

00:42:10.110 --> 00:42:13.489
work until they had to do it.

00:42:13.489 --> 00:42:15.030
But as one guy put
it to me recently,

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:16.446
the nice thing
about bitcoin is it

00:42:16.446 --> 00:42:18.600
is going through all
these growing pains.

00:42:18.600 --> 00:42:22.200
And so it is becoming kind
of more trusted, in a sense,

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:26.550
simply because it has shown its
resilience despite scandals,

00:42:26.550 --> 00:42:28.350
despite the hacks of
bitcoin exchanges,

00:42:28.350 --> 00:42:31.450
despite some bitcoin
startups failing, and so on.

00:42:33.825 --> 00:42:34.775
AUDIENCE: Hey there.

00:42:34.775 --> 00:42:35.250
My name's Nick.

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:35.730
BRIAN PATRICK EHA: Hey.

00:42:35.730 --> 00:42:38.180
AUDIENCE: So my question's
around the ethereum network

00:42:38.180 --> 00:42:40.370
and really the
speculation around moving

00:42:40.370 --> 00:42:42.299
to a proof of stakes concept.

00:42:42.299 --> 00:42:43.340
BRIAN PATRICK EHA: Mm-hm.

00:42:43.340 --> 00:42:44.930
AUDIENCE: So I guess
the question is,

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:46.730
is that what's stopping
big players from entering

00:42:46.730 --> 00:42:48.854
the game at that point in
a proof-of-stakes network

00:42:48.854 --> 00:42:52.040
or a proof-of-stakes concept
and them taking a large market

00:42:52.040 --> 00:42:55.300
share on the computing
power, essentially

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:58.540
removing maybe the concept
of the decentralized network?

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:00.860
Or is that not even
a problem at all?

00:43:00.860 --> 00:43:02.443
BRIAN PATRICK EHA:
Well, to be honest,

00:43:02.443 --> 00:43:04.820
I'm not as much of an
expert on the underpinnings

00:43:04.820 --> 00:43:06.940
of the ethereum network as I--

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:09.650
I don't know quite as much
about the proof-of-stakes system

00:43:09.650 --> 00:43:11.810
and how all of that is
handled as I do about, like,

00:43:11.810 --> 00:43:16.040
the proof-of-work system
that bitcoin uses.

00:43:16.040 --> 00:43:18.770
But yeah, I mean, I think
people do have concerns

00:43:18.770 --> 00:43:21.440
that some of the power
in the ethereum network

00:43:21.440 --> 00:43:24.800
is already concentrated
in too few hands.

00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:28.700
I mean, the fact that the
network forked last year

00:43:28.700 --> 00:43:31.010
and essentially split into
two versions-- you have

00:43:31.010 --> 00:43:33.567
what they call ethereum, but
it's actually the new ethereum.

00:43:33.567 --> 00:43:35.900
And then you have what they
call ethereum classic, which

00:43:35.900 --> 00:43:38.870
is the original network.

00:43:38.870 --> 00:43:42.530
And that happened because
there was a big hack and theft

00:43:42.530 --> 00:43:44.840
of this one investment
vehicle that was running

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:46.370
on the ethereum network.

00:43:46.370 --> 00:43:49.460
And millions of dollars worth
of ether were stolen from it.

00:43:49.460 --> 00:43:53.880
And so the top leaders
of the ethereum network,

00:43:53.880 --> 00:43:56.870
including the guy
mostly credited

00:43:56.870 --> 00:43:59.150
as its creator, this guy
named Vitalik Buterin,

00:43:59.150 --> 00:44:02.930
they decided, OK, we're
going to roll this back

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:06.080
and make it so that this
thief doesn't profit

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:07.610
from his ill-gotten gains.

00:44:07.610 --> 00:44:10.190
But the way to do that
in a blockchain network

00:44:10.190 --> 00:44:12.410
is that you basically
have to fork the network.

00:44:12.410 --> 00:44:15.920
And if everyone had
agreed, then maybe they

00:44:15.920 --> 00:44:19.040
would have all moved
over to the new network.

00:44:19.040 --> 00:44:20.490
But some didn't.

00:44:20.490 --> 00:44:22.430
And some people
decided to continue

00:44:22.430 --> 00:44:25.760
putting developing resources
and time and effort

00:44:25.760 --> 00:44:27.410
into the original network.

00:44:27.410 --> 00:44:32.120
And so now you have actually two
different networks, one which

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:35.030
has stayed sort of immutable,
and no transactions have ever

00:44:35.030 --> 00:44:38.060
been rolled back, and then this
new one that actually today is

00:44:38.060 --> 00:44:41.360
much more valuable in
terms of its market cap

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:47.210
but which some people think
is really not so trustworthy

00:44:47.210 --> 00:44:51.267
because it's possible that
some of these big stakeholders,

00:44:51.267 --> 00:44:52.850
at any time they
don't like something,

00:44:52.850 --> 00:44:55.550
they might choose to undo it.

00:44:55.550 --> 00:44:59.266
And the only thing, in a sense,
stopping them from doing that--

00:44:59.266 --> 00:45:00.700
well, maybe not the only thing.

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:03.980
But the main thing
people are relying on

00:45:03.980 --> 00:45:07.340
is they just say,
well, we won't, right?

00:45:07.340 --> 00:45:10.040
Another issue that
I have with ethereum

00:45:10.040 --> 00:45:13.850
is that I think it's a bit
more of a, I don't want

00:45:13.850 --> 00:45:15.800
to say exactly a
cult of personality,

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:18.140
but there is a bit of
a cult of personality

00:45:18.140 --> 00:45:20.870
around this guy, Vitalik
Buterin, who's incredibly

00:45:20.870 --> 00:45:23.240
young, I mean, clearly
brilliant, I mean,

00:45:23.240 --> 00:45:26.630
a real genius, but
this really young guy

00:45:26.630 --> 00:45:29.720
who is known as the creator
of it and co-founder of it.

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:34.070
And "Fortune" actually
perpetrated a hoax on Sunday

00:45:34.070 --> 00:45:36.920
night that Vitalik
Buterin had died.

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:40.520
And almost instantly, $4
billion were wiped off

00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:43.610
the market cap of ethereum
because (CHUCKLING) people

00:45:43.610 --> 00:45:46.970
said, you know--

00:45:46.970 --> 00:45:49.310
whereas with bitcoin,
the creator--

00:45:49.310 --> 00:45:53.180
this guy whose identity is still
not known, Satoshi Nakamoto--

00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:56.060
after the first couple of
years of working on the system

00:45:56.060 --> 00:45:58.160
alongside other developers
he had recruited,

00:45:58.160 --> 00:46:00.950
he walked away and just
vanished into the night.

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:03.140
And bitcoin has continued
to thrive after that.

00:46:03.140 --> 00:46:05.840
I think that was one of
the last brilliant things

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:09.440
he did was that he chose to walk
away from it to see if it could

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:12.680
stand on its own, to not let
it be a cult of personality,

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:16.670
to not constantly
have people just going

00:46:16.670 --> 00:46:19.400
to him as the Oracle
of Delphi to make

00:46:19.400 --> 00:46:21.660
every decision for them.

00:46:21.660 --> 00:46:24.050
Ethereum still needs to take
those training wheels off,

00:46:24.050 --> 00:46:24.770
in a sense.

00:46:24.770 --> 00:46:27.420
And Vitalik has
said, to his credit,

00:46:27.420 --> 00:46:30.680
that he'd like to take a
step back at some point.

00:46:30.680 --> 00:46:32.430
But that hasn't
really happened yet.

