00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:46.800
AUDIENCE: Hoping you can touch
upon your opinion on, like,

00:46:46.800 --> 00:46:49.582
the block-size debate
that's currently going on.

00:46:49.582 --> 00:46:51.290
BRIAN PATRICK EHA:
Yeah, no, I don't have

00:46:51.290 --> 00:46:53.865
a super strong opinion on that.

00:46:53.865 --> 00:46:55.370
I mean, it gets
really technical.

00:46:55.370 --> 00:46:58.310
And there are these
different competing proposals

00:46:58.310 --> 00:47:02.180
for how the network
should be scaled up,

00:47:02.180 --> 00:47:07.292
as I said, to meet the needs
of a growing user base.

00:47:07.292 --> 00:47:09.500
Basically, transactions--
the reason that it's called

00:47:09.500 --> 00:47:13.430
the blockchain network is that
transactions are processed

00:47:13.430 --> 00:47:15.170
and put into blocks--

00:47:15.170 --> 00:47:16.730
these kind of batches.

00:47:16.730 --> 00:47:19.250
And every 10 minutes,
approximately a new block

00:47:19.250 --> 00:47:22.520
is created, and it's added
to the existing blockchain.

00:47:22.520 --> 00:47:25.220
So you have this
immutable ledger

00:47:25.220 --> 00:47:29.730
that records every transaction
going back to January 2009

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:32.460
in this giant
de-centralized ledger

00:47:32.460 --> 00:47:34.882
that you can think
of as a chain.

00:47:34.882 --> 00:47:36.590
But the problem is
that these blocks only

00:47:36.590 --> 00:47:37.800
have a certain capacity.

00:47:37.800 --> 00:47:40.760
Each block can only hold a
certain number of transactions.

00:47:40.760 --> 00:47:43.966
And as the network has
gotten bigger and bigger,

00:47:43.966 --> 00:47:46.340
as there have been more and
more transactions, whether it

00:47:46.340 --> 00:47:49.980
be spending it as currency,
or trading activity,

00:47:49.980 --> 00:47:53.900
or what have you, those
blocks have been--

00:47:53.900 --> 00:47:56.000
they've gotten full, basically.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:57.980
And although, as I
said, the transactions

00:47:57.980 --> 00:48:01.280
themselves are still happening
instantaneously, the time

00:48:01.280 --> 00:48:05.210
it's taking for miners
to take new transactions,

00:48:05.210 --> 00:48:07.100
confirm them, verify
that they're valid,

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:09.020
and thus add them
to new blocks that

00:48:09.020 --> 00:48:12.660
can be added to the overall
blockchain, it's taking longer.

00:48:12.660 --> 00:48:14.409
There's been basically
this slowdown.

00:48:14.409 --> 00:48:15.950
And so there are
different proposals.

00:48:15.950 --> 00:48:17.840
Some people are
saying, well, let's

00:48:17.840 --> 00:48:21.327
make the blocks twice as big
as they currently are, OK?

00:48:21.327 --> 00:48:23.660
Let's make them four times
as big as they currently are.

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:26.510
Let's do this other thing
and make them twice as

00:48:26.510 --> 00:48:27.825
big as they currently are.

00:48:27.825 --> 00:48:28.950
And there's all this stuff.

00:48:28.950 --> 00:48:31.850
One of the concerns about
making the blocks bigger

00:48:31.850 --> 00:48:33.500
is that then the size--

00:48:33.500 --> 00:48:37.610
I mean, the data storage size
of the overall blockchain--

00:48:37.610 --> 00:48:39.620
will become much, much bigger.

00:48:39.620 --> 00:48:42.530
And it will be much harder
for smaller operators

00:48:42.530 --> 00:48:45.200
to still participate
in the network, which

00:48:45.200 --> 00:48:47.690
could potentially
concentrate power

00:48:47.690 --> 00:48:50.570
in fewer hands on the network.

00:48:50.570 --> 00:48:52.130
I that's one of the concerns.

00:48:52.130 --> 00:48:56.420
And then there are
other concerns,

00:48:56.420 --> 00:48:59.900
if you can call them that, like
the fact that the way right

00:48:59.900 --> 00:49:04.460
now to get the miners to confirm
your transactions faster if you

00:49:04.460 --> 00:49:07.580
really need them to be
confirmed quickly is you

00:49:07.580 --> 00:49:10.970
pay them a little mining
fee, a little transaction fee

00:49:10.970 --> 00:49:12.410
basically.

00:49:12.410 --> 00:49:14.450
Now some people think
this is a real problem.

00:49:14.450 --> 00:49:16.262
We have, over the
last couple of years,

00:49:16.262 --> 00:49:18.220
we're seeing these
transaction fees get higher.

00:49:18.220 --> 00:49:20.450
It used to be that
bitcoin transactions were

00:49:20.450 --> 00:49:21.350
almost costless.

00:49:21.350 --> 00:49:22.850
And that was one
of their advantages

00:49:22.850 --> 00:49:26.540
over things like using
credit cards or other--

00:49:26.540 --> 00:49:28.215
Western Union and so on.

00:49:28.215 --> 00:49:30.590
But if these transaction fees
are going to keep climbing,

00:49:30.590 --> 00:49:33.350
then that seems to
take away at least part

00:49:33.350 --> 00:49:36.380
of bitcoin's advantage, right?

00:49:36.380 --> 00:49:38.030
But on the other
hand, the mining

00:49:38.030 --> 00:49:39.990
pools-- some of the big
mining pools in China,

00:49:39.990 --> 00:49:42.440
for instance-- they seem to
like these transaction fees

00:49:42.440 --> 00:49:45.090
just fine, for obvious reasons.

00:49:45.090 --> 00:49:47.090
And so there is a
bit of a battle.

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:48.620
I mean, there are
some developers,

00:49:48.620 --> 00:49:51.200
there some bitcoin
companies, other stakeholders

00:49:51.200 --> 00:49:54.340
that have agreed on
certain proposals.

00:49:54.340 --> 00:49:56.840
And then there are others that
are holding out against them.

00:49:56.840 --> 00:50:00.440
And in many cases,
it's the miners.

00:50:00.440 --> 00:50:03.560
And the difficulty there
is that the developers

00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:05.810
can create whatever version
of the software they want.

00:50:05.810 --> 00:50:07.768
They can all agree, this
is what we need to do.

00:50:07.768 --> 00:50:09.680
This is the best
version of the software.

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:12.650
A lot of the bitcoin
entrepreneurs and companies

00:50:12.650 --> 00:50:15.110
and investors can agree.

00:50:15.110 --> 00:50:18.290
But in order to actually move
to that version of the network,

00:50:18.290 --> 00:50:22.220
you need to get at least 51%
of the total processing power

00:50:22.220 --> 00:50:24.560
on the network to
agree to start running

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:26.180
that version of the software.

00:50:26.180 --> 00:50:29.090
You need a majority to agree.

00:50:29.090 --> 00:50:34.070
So that has been if you want
to call it holding back some

00:50:34.070 --> 00:50:36.530
of the progress in the network.

00:50:36.530 --> 00:50:38.210
On the other hand,
it's kind of great

00:50:38.210 --> 00:50:40.880
that you have a system that
can't be easily changed, right?

00:50:40.880 --> 00:50:43.400
It's almost like the political
system of the United States,

00:50:43.400 --> 00:50:45.980
that sometimes the
gridlock is not a bug.

00:50:45.980 --> 00:50:48.980
It's a feature because otherwise
each new administration

00:50:48.980 --> 00:50:50.690
that comes in could
just completely

00:50:50.690 --> 00:50:53.960
undo everything and just
wipe the slate clean, right?

00:50:53.960 --> 00:50:58.670
So this is one of the
potential advantages

00:50:58.670 --> 00:51:00.610
of new cryptocurrencies
is that they

00:51:00.610 --> 00:51:01.860
might be a little more nimble.

00:51:01.860 --> 00:51:02.910
They might be more agile.

00:51:02.910 --> 00:51:05.120
They might have better
governance systems

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:06.320
in some sense.

00:51:06.320 --> 00:51:08.300
But it could be
that bitcoin will

00:51:08.300 --> 00:51:12.380
take on this elder statesman
role, where it, out of all

00:51:12.380 --> 00:51:16.790
these assets, it becomes
the most stable and trusted,

00:51:16.790 --> 00:51:18.860
the one that's least
subject to change.

00:51:18.860 --> 00:51:21.080
And it might turn out
to be a little bit

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:24.020
of a tortoise compared to
the hare of the others.

00:51:24.020 --> 00:51:25.790
But sometimes you
want a tortoise.

